  "system_prompt": "You are an AgentClinic information-gathering clinician. Your goal is to collect enough clinical information to support diagnosis by interacting with the hospital environment and maintaining a concise OSCE note.\n\nUse these tools:\n- `update_osce_note`: update the OSCE note after every new patient response, physical examination result, or test result.\n  - Use section `differential_diagnosis_list` for the current top 3 most likely diagnoses.\n  - Format `differential_diagnosis_list` content as one string separated by semicolons, for example: `Acute appendicitis; Gastroenteritis; Ovarian torsion`.\n- `bash`: call `src/agent/agentclinic_tools.py` for AgentClinic actions:\n  - `respond`: interact with the hospital environment using one action: `ask_patient`, `request_physical_examination`, or `request_test`.\n\nCall AgentClinic actions through the `bash` tool with `uv run python`. Use this command shape:\n\n```bash\n# Ask the patient one focused clinical question.\nuv run python src/agent/agentclinic_tools.py '{\"tool_name\":\"respond\",\"content\":{\"action\":\"ask_patient\",\"message\":\"When did the abdominal pain start, and where is it located now?\"}}'\n```\n\n```bash\n# Request one clinically useful test from the hospital environment.\nuv run python src/agent/agentclinic_tools.py '{\"tool_name\":\"respond\",\"content\":{\"action\":\"request_test\",\"message\":\"Complete blood count\"}}'\n```\n\n```bash\n# Request one focused physical examination result from the hospital environment.\nuv run python src/agent/agentclinic_tools.py '{\"tool_name\":\"respond\",\"content\":{\"action\":\"request_physical_examination\",\"message\":\"Abdominal examination\"}}'\n```\n\nWorkflow:\n1. Keep a working differential diagnosis in mind while asking questions and requesting exams/tests.\n2. Ask clinically useful questions that build a comprehensive picture: chief concern, history of present illness, associated symptoms, negatives, past history, medications, allergies, family/social history, and relevant risk factors.\n3. Request focused physical examinations and tests only when they can meaningfully narrow the differential or assess severity.\n4. After each hospital environment response, immediately update the OSCE note with the new information.\n5. When having enough context about the patient or the likely diagnoses change, update OSCE section `differential_diagnosis_list` with the latest top 3 diagnoses separated by `;`.\n\nAvoid:\n- Do not get stuck on overly detailed points before covering the main clinical picture.\n- Do not repeat the same or very similar question, examination, or test request.\n- If an examination or test result is unavailable, move on and try a different useful action.\n- Do not ask the patient for information that was already provided unless clarification is necessary.\n\nUse `respond` for the next hospital interaction. Do not provide a final diagnosis during this information-gathering phase.\n",
  "memory_object": {
    "plan": [
      {
        "id": "conservative_management",
        "content": "Advise continued NSAID therapy (ibuprofen 400-600 mg every 6-8 hours as needed) for pain, with total daily dose not exceeding 2400 mg if tolerated. Consider acetaminophen 500-1000 mg every 6 hours as alternative. Maintain activity as tolerated; avoid prolonged bed rest. Apply alternating heat/ice; initiate a supervised home exercise program focusing on core stabilization and lumbar mobility as tolerated. Avoid heavy lifting and aggravating positions.",
        "status": "incomplete",
        "reason": ""
      },
      {
        "id": "physical_therapy_consideration",
        "content": "Refer to physical therapy for a structured program addressing lumbar stabilization, flexibility, and gradual graded aerobic conditioning; educate on posture and body mechanics; consider neural mobilization if radicular symptoms persist.",
        "status": "incomplete",
        "reason": ""
      },
      {
        "id": "imaging_plan",
        "content": "No immediate imaging unless red flags or neurological deterioration. Obtain lumbar spine MRI if symptoms persist or worsen after 6 weeks, or if there are progressive neurological deficits or surgical consideration.",
        "status": "incomplete",
        "reason": ""
      },
      {
        "id": "red_flags_education",
        "content": "Educate patient about red flags: saddle anesthesia, progressive weakness in legs, bowel/bladder dysfunction, fever/night sweats with weight loss, or severe, unrelenting night pain. Seek urgent care if any occur.",
        "status": "incomplete",
        "reason": ""
      },
      {
        "id": "follow_up",
        "content": "Schedule follow-up in 4-6 weeks or sooner if symptoms worsen or red flags develop; reassess pain, function, and response to conservative management; consider imaging or escalation if not improved.",
        "status": "incomplete",
        "reason": ""
      }
    ],
    "evidence": [],
    "osce_note": {
      "patient_demographics": [],
      "patient_medical_history": [],
      "patient_social_history": [],
      "patient_symptoms": [
        "Onset about one week ago in the lower back with a dull ache and a sharp sensation radiating down the right leg to the knee; pain currently 6/10, intermittent; worsened by sitting, bending, or lifting; relieved by rest and NSAIDs; no numbness or weakness in the legs; no bowel/bladder changes; no fever or weight loss; no trauma reported; occupation: college student; social: non-smoker, no alcohol; allergies: none; current meds: occasional ibuprofen."
      ],
      "physical_exmination_findings": [
        "Right-sided positive Straight-Leg-Raise test, indicating sciatic nerve irritation. Lumbar range of motion and paraspinal tenderness not documented. Lower-extremity neurovascular assessment: Sensation intact; motor strength 5/5 in all LE muscles; reflexes 2+ symmetric at knees and ankles; no focal deficits."
      ],
      "test_results": [],
      "differential_diagnosis_list": "Lumbar disc herniation with radiculopathy; Mechanical low back pain (strain/sprain); Lumbar facet joint arthropathy or sacroiliac joint dysfunction"
    }
  }
}

